# shepherd-dev — supervised development

When the user asks to develop a feature under supervision (or names shepherd-dev),
drive the `shepherd-dev` CLI in the integrated terminal. Do NOT edit the files
yourself — a sandboxed worker proposes the change and the user decides what gets in.

## How

1. Once per repo: `shepherd-dev init` — initializes the workspace and detects the
   test gate (saved to `.shepherd-dev.json`).
2. Develop: `shepherd-dev run "<the feature in natural language>"`.
   - The worker runs sandboxed and only PROPOSES changes; nothing is written yet.
   - Show the user the report (attempts, gate result, reviewer verdict) and the diff.
3. **Wait for the user to accept or reject — never settle on your own.**
   - Accept: `shepherd-dev settle <run-ref>` (writes the files into the worktree).
   - Reject: `shepherd-dev settle <run-ref> --reject` (discards it).

## Notes

- `--repo` and `--test-cmd` are inferred from inside the repo; pass them only to override.
- Two coordinated features at once: `shepherd-dev run2 "<A>" "<B>"`, then `shepherd-dev settle-par <id>`.
- Confine scope with `--allowed-prefix <path>` (repeatable); tests-only with `--mode tests`.
- The worker is a headless `claude` session, so an authenticated `claude` CLI is
  required — this is separate from Cursor's own AI, which does not power the worker.
- Nothing touches the working tree until the user accepts; the git commit stays theirs.
